    <section id="home">
        <p>Explore the impact of light pollution on our environment and find out how you can help combat it!</p>
        <img src="https://www.pnas.org/cms/10.1073/pnas.2309539120/asset/2a79400a-cb9b-4f86-8225-9481c1756600/assets/images/large/pnas.2309539120fig01.jpg" style="max-width: 30%; height: 50%; margin-left: 15%;">

        <h3>What is Light Pollution?</h3>
        <p>Light pollution refers to the excessive or misdirected artificial light produced by streetlights, buildings, and vehicles. It not only obscures our view of stars but also disrupts ecosystems and negatively affects human health by interfering with natural circadian rhythms.</p>
        <p>Light Pollution is the Presence of any unwanted, or Excessive artificial lighting. In descriptive sense, the term light pollution refers to the Effects of any poorly implemented lighting sources, during the day or night. Light Pollution can be understood not only as a phenomenon resulting from Specific source or kind of pollution, but also as a contributor to the wider, collective impact of various sources of Pollution.</p> 
        <p> Although this type of pollution can exist throughout the day, its Effects are magnified during the night with the contrast of the sky's darkness. It has been Estimated that 83 percent of the world's people live under light - polluted Skies. and that 23% of world land areas are affected by skyglow The area affected by artificial illumination Continues to increase. A major side Effect of urbanization, light pollution is blamed for compromising health, disrupt Ecosystems and Spoiling aesthetic Environments.</p>
        <p>Studies shows that urban areas are more at risk.Globally, it has increased by at least 49% from 1992 to 2017.Light pollution is caused by inefficient or unnecessary use of Artificial light. Specific categories of light pollutions include light frees pass, over- illumination, glare, light cutter, and sky G/ow. A Single offending light source often falls into more than once of these Categories.</p>

        <h3>Impacts of Light Pollution</h3>
        <p>Light pollution affects both ecosystems and human health. Many animals rely on natural light cycles, and excessive artificial light can disrupt these patterns. For humans, exposure to light at night can lead to sleep disorders and increased stress.</p>

    </section>

    <section id="effects">
        <h2>Effects on Environment</h2>
        <img src="https://www.led-professional.com/technologies-research/research-confirms-that-light-pollution-can-suppress-melatonin-production-in-humans-and-animals/@@images/image-1200-fbb5a560e277363de38593c249821a7e.jpeg" style="max-width: 30%; height: 50%; margin-left: 15%;">
        <p>Light pollution has profound effects on both wildlife and humans. Many species depend on natural light patterns for navigation, reproduction, and hunting. For instance, sea turtles rely on moonlight to find their way to the ocean, while birds may get disoriented by artificial lights during migration.</p>
        <p>In urban areas, light pollution can also contribute to energy waste, as unnecessary lighting increases electricity consumption and greenhouse gas emissions. This not only harms the environment but also affects our climate.</p>
        <h3>Causes of light Pollution:-</h3>
        <p>Urbanization is a very large source of light pollution because cities are usually the well- lighted presentation of buildings, street lights along with other artificial light sources. A Study by Gaston ef at (2013). showed that urban areas are responsible for 90% of the global light pollution, which causes serious environmental problems. furthermore, poor lightning design, such as implements that are able to shine light out ward, that increasing the light area, is a big part of the problem (Kybo ef al 2015). Shifting to LED which is Energy - Efficient technology. consisted, can lead to lower blue light Emissions which have been connected to some of the biggest light pollution problems. (sweeney et al 2020).Ecological Efforts of Light Pollutions</p>
        <p>Research underlines that. luminous pollution, on the one hand, shifts the dally activities of Nocturnal animals, on the other hand, influences nutrition, breeding, and migration forms. For instance, sea turtles take signals from mature light cues to go to the ocean when they hatch, but the tortoises may even be . misled by the bright lights Witherington $ Bjorndal, 1991. I cannot but wonder if the main data of Bennie et al. (2016) also support the idea that artificial light at night is the reason for the decrease in the number of insects, and in this way, next hurting mainly the insect eating birds and other predators Which feed on these insects.</p>
        <h3>Human Health Impact of light Pollution</h3>
        <p>Light Pollution also causes serious problems for people's health. Artificial light Exposure at night might interfere with the circadian rhythm, thus Causing Sleep disorders and increasing the risks of chronic diseases like obesity and depression (Haim $ Zubeidat, 2015). People working in shifts or the population residing under brilliantly lit places are more at risk, and the who has thereby identified light pollution as a potential threat to health (WHO. 2019)
        </p>
        <h2><u>Light Pollution Affects Wildlife</u></h2>
        <img src="https://wec.ifas.ufl.edu/extension/gc/harmony/LightWildlife_files/image002.jpg" style="max-width: 30%; height: 50%; margin-left: 15%;">
        <p>Light pollution—the luminous orange glow that haloes cities and suburbs—threatens wildlife by disrupting biological rhythms and otherwise interfering with the behavior of nocturnal animals, new research shows. Now a movement is under way to turn off the lights, or at least turn them down, for the sake of all creatures that frequent the night.
        "Wildlife species have evolved on this planet with biological rhythms—changing that has profound effects," said Travis Longcore, a biogeographer with the Urban Wildlands Group in Los Angeles, who with colleague Catherine Rich, co-organized a conference last year on "Ecological Consequences of Artificial Night Lighting."</p>
        <h3>Birds at Risk</h3>
        <p>Artificial lighting seems to be taking the largest toll on bird populations. Nocturnal birds use the moon and stars for navigation during their bi-annual migrations.

            "When they fly through a brightly-lit area, they become disoriented," said Michael Mesure, executive director of the Fatal Light Awareness Program (FLAP), a Toronto-based environmental organization. The birds often crash into brilliantly-lit broadcast towers or buildings, or circle them until they drop from exhaustion.
            
            "Over 450 bird species that migrate at night across North America are susceptible to collisions with night-lit towers, including threatened or endangered species like the cerulean warbler and Henslow's sparrow," Mesure said.
            
            Sometimes whole flocks collide with over-lit structures. According to Mesure, over two consecutive nights in 1954, 50,000 birds died at Warner Robins Air Force Base, Georgia, when they followed lights straight into the ground. And in 1981, over 10,000 birds slammed into floodlit smokestacks at the Hydrox Generating Plant near Kingston, Ontario.
            
            Seabirds are also at risk, said Bill Montevecchi, a marine ornithologist at Memorial University of Newfoundland, in St. John's, Canada.
            
            Some, like the tiny Leach's storm petrel, feed offshore on bioluminescent plankton—so are particularly drawn to light. The birds may be fatally attracted to lighthouses, offshore drilling platforms, and the high-intensity lamps used by fishermen to lure squid to the surface.
            
            "It's not that we wouldn't expect birds to die from human activities—but it is our responsibility to minimize that mortality," said Montevecchi.</p>
        <h3>Reptiles Affected by Light</h3>
        <p>Light pollution also endangers sea turtles. Beaches in sections of Florida's highly developed coastline are nesting ground for rare loggerhead, leatherback and green turtles. Bright lights nearby discourage females from coming ashore to nest.

            Newly hatched turtles need a dark night sky to orient themselves toward the sea, but artificial lights behind beaches lure them away.
            
            "Hatchlings are attracted to lights and crawl inland, or crawl aimlessly down the beach, sometimes until dawn, when terrestrial predators or birds get them," said Michael Salmon, a biologist at Florida Atlantic University in Boca Raton, Florida.
            
            Coastal counties in Florida have passed ordinances that residents turn off beachfront lights during turtle nesting season, but they are not always enforced—and they don't address the larger problem of sky glow near cities, says Salmon.
            
            Researchers are examining the effects of artificial lighting on many creatures. To avoid predators, some animals—like some snakes, salamanders or frogs—restrict their movements under a full moon and tend to hunt more on moonless nights. Others forage just after dusk. But some lighting never allows darkness to fall.</p>
        <h3>Artificial Light and Feeding, Hunting, and Hormones</h3>
        <p>A recent experiment sheds light on the light-pollution problem for salamanders. Ecologists Sharon Wise and Bryant Buchanan from Utica College strung white holiday lights along transects near Mountain Lake Biological Station in Pembroke, Virginia, to test the effects of artificial lighting on the amphibians—which normally emerge from beneath leaf litter to hunt about an hour after dusk..

            "We found that when lights are on, they stay hidden for an additional hour," said Wise. "The later they come out, the less food they may be able to eat."
            
            Buchanan also discovered that some tree frogs stop calling in brightly-lit areas. "If the males aren't calling, they're not reproducing," he said.
            
            He is also concerned about the way light affects physical development. Lab studies show that the amount of light exposure affects DNA synthesis and the production of hormones—hormones that regulate everything from how much fat the frogs store for the winter to when they produce eggs.
            
            "Frogs living in constantly illuminated environments may not be getting the proper signals," he said. "We need to take the next step and do field studies to find out."
            
            There are few studies on the effect of light pollution on mammals, although all 986 species of bats, most smaller carnivores and rodents, 20 percent of primates, and 80 percent of marsupials are nocturnal.
            
            "Thus it would be surprising if night lighting did not have significant effects on mammals," said Paul Beier, a wildlife ecologist at Northern Arizona University in Flagstaff. He found that pumas traveling at night avoid brightly-lit areas, causing them to miss crucial landscape linkages.
            
            Fireflies may not mate normally near incandescent light because it mimics the spectrum they create when they light up. Moths may lose essential defensive behaviors when near artificial light, making them vulnerable to predators; billions of moths and other nocturnal insects are killed each year at lights.</p>
        <h3>Dark Skies as a Natural Resource</h3>
        <p>Designating a dark sky as a natural resource which is as worthy of protection as an old growth forest or a scenic river may seem odd, but biologists worry about the ultimate impact caused by this little-understood ecological disturbance.

            Saving energy also makes economic and political sense. The International Dark-Sky Association in Tucson, Arizona, an environmental group, estimates that one-third of all lighting in the U.S. is wasted, at an annual cost of about 30 million barrels of oil and 8.2 million tons of coal—a total of about U.S. $2 billion.
            
            For wild creatures, research can provide guidelines about helping to preserve biodiversity by adjusting the light. The Fatal Light Awareness Program, for example, has worked with Toronto agencies and businesses to dim down or turn off excess lighting during migration season.
            
            Unlike most ecological problems, light pollution has a solution, Mesure points out: "At the flick of a switch, this one could disappear."
            
             
            
            Guynup, Sharon. "Light Pollution Taking Toll on Wildlife, Eco-Groups Say." National Geographic Today April 17, 2003. National Geographic News @ news.nationalgeographic.com. Accessed on February 8, 2007</p>
        <h3>Types of Light Pollution</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Skyglow:</strong> The brightening of the night sky over populated areas.</li>
            <li><strong>Glare:</strong> Excessive brightness that causes visual discomfort.</li>
            <li><strong>Light Trespass:</strong> Unwanted light that spills over into areas where it is not needed.</li>
            <li><strong>Clutter:</strong> Confusing and excessive groupings of light sources.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="solutions">
        <h2>Illuminating Solutions: </h2>
        <img src="https://img.haikudeck.com/mg/LqfepnlpMB_1416447592088.jpg" alt="Solutions to Light Pollution" style="max-width: 30%; height: 50%; margin-left: 15%;">
        <h4> 1)   Data Collection</h4>
        <p>Dato for this study were Collected through an exhaustive literature review using academic databases such as google scholar, JSTOR, 8 pub Med. The Keyword related to light pollution and its environmental impacts were used in the search such as "light pollution", "sustainable pollution of light pollution" and "Artificial light at night". The Data was Extracted in a systematic manner by identifying the main pieces of the contribution such as the authors, the objectives, the key findings, and the recommendation for actions. Besides, relevant case studies were also scrutinized in order to provide concrete Examples of successful interventions and they were studied with regard to the setting, types of solutions Applied, and related outcomes</p>
        <h4>2) Case Study!-</h4>
        <p>Case Studies arealso a great source of information for light pollution.
            It give practical Examples of the Success stories of interventions against light pollution. The following Key points were invested in the case studies:
            → Geographic context lie, urban and rural Areas
            → Methods of intervention such as smart lightning and compliance with the regulations.
            → An overview of the Effectiveness of these interventions, such as through quantitative measures - eg. light levels have dropped & energy Savings have been achieved and qualitative factors like community Engagement and biodiversity preservation.
            </p>
        <h4>3) Data Analysis!-</h4>
        <p>The information that was acquired from the literature Review and Case Studies was Combined in a thematic manner to reveal the patterns and effective Strategies that might be used in the resolution of light pollution. The analysis thus utilized the following !
            → Thematic Coding: - Every Element of the literature was sequentially coded by the themed Kind, such as technology, community particulation, Policy measures, and nature- based Solutions that are used, etc.
            → Comparative Analysis:- The schools that have applied similar actions were Compared in the degree of positive consequences by the time and method of their utilization. This was done by reviewing the strength and weakness Scenarios in different Cases.</p>
        <h4>4) Ethical Considerations:-</h4>
        <p>This research utilized documents that are publicly available and cases Studies were also used in the research .
            Ethical Component such as citing power Sources of the information and not using other researches information illegally was the main point of reference. In addition, the study further indicates that team work of various allies is crucial and Stake holder participation is one of the ways of dealing with light pollution issues.
            </p>
        <h4></h4>
        <p></p>
        <p>Light pollution remediation includes both innovative new technologies and regulatory. measures. Smart lightning systems enabled by the latest technologies, which offer the brightness level in accordance with Realtime meteorological conditions, are successful in reducing re abundant illumination (EPA, 2020).In addition, the proper lighting design, such as fixtures fully Shielding the objects of lighting that are directed below, can Considerably diminish the light Spillage and glare (International Dark-Sky Association, 2021). Public awareness campaigns can contribute to the creation of a culture that values high levels of natural darkness, thus prompting people and municipalities to adopt more eco-friendly lighting Practices. However, the introduction of Sky ordinances in several places is a manifestation of policy actions capability to mitigation.</p>
        <h3>Data Collection and Case Studies</h3>
        <p>This study selectively reviewed a vast range of literature on scientific findings on the subject of light pollution , which enabled the identification of its sources and consequences ultimately. It was disclosed in the study findings that around 90% of the light pollution in the world is generated in lights when luminescence in the urban settings highlights this concern even more. Particularly, the lighting installed on the external cladding, gerly called poor exterior lighting design or skyglow, has been one of the identified reasons for the escalating light pollution (Kyba et al., 2015). In these cases, inappropriate designs that currently guise as aesthetic such as more luminescence emitting fixtures not only consuming higher energy consumption for unnecessary lighting effects result to an increased need for lighting at night but also dark harm the immediate environment and occupants in it.</p>
        <p>From 1992 to 2017, light pollution levels increased by approximately 49% globally, showing that there exists a more pressing requirement for remedies to be introduced with immediate effect. Over three-quarters of this increase is due to the high levels of urbanization which trap more people in areas where there is more light and hardly any darkness</p>
        <h3>Types of Projects and Case Studies</h3>
        <p>The study conducted some case studies on sample projects that have worked towards improving lighting in towns, cities and rural areas. For example, with the newest technology available, cities such as Los Angeles and Paris have significantly managed to reduce lighting and energy consumption in an overall proportion. In other words, the introduction of energy-saving LED bulbs in the cities not only helped in the control of excessive illumination but promoted better interaction among the area communities. This could also be seen very well and well-treated through integrated pest management systems. The implementation of which effectively helped in mains incidentally most of these systems helped in-housing, lighting pollution and areas of combat fees energies activities in lowering impacts. People complained less on this and even ended up-signing positive petition letters. Residents towards their environment hence were educated thanks to community outreach resulting in an increased sensitivity after the interventions integrated with promising results technological solutions led residents to be more appreciative of nature.</p>
        <h3>Thematic Analysis</h3>
        <p>Effective interventions to moderate light pollution have been classified according to the thematic analysis of the data that was made for all the categories namely:

            The craving adoption led to the technology since the shift to the usage of the LED lights has proved to be most effective. The LED lights use less energy and are customizable to filter the blue lights which have led to some exhaustion in the health and ecological sphere (Sweeney et al., 2020).</p>
        <p>The effects of citizen involvement for light pollution reduction cannot be overlooked as campaigns against these types of pollution have to make it to the local level in order to change public behavior. These programs result in the people attaching value to natural darkness and consciously adopting practice of sound lighting principles by the residents. It was established that light pollution measures had been integrated in communities which resulted in more appreciation for natural scenery as well as contentment with the local environment.</p>
        <p>It is critical that policy maker use specific laws to try to manage the problem of excessive lighting. This is in spite of decrease light pollution tendencies in municipalities where the policies for lighting have been effective. Such legislations are advantageous not only in the enforcement of lighting codes but also in encouraging proficiency in the construction industry and the planning of cities.
        </p>
        <p>Nature-Based Solutions: You integrate natural techniques, such as creating wildlife corridors that are dark and the preservation of natural caves as strategical ways to deal with light pollution with respect to the environment. Rather than serve urban needs alone; some of these crowded cities may have ecological healthy development oriented growth.
        </p>
        <h3>Comparative Analysis</h3>
        <p>Upon analyzing case studies it can be inferred how metropolitan intervention influenced specific development of light pollution. Cities that used the strategies, management and information shared within technology, policies and community organisations, achieved the objectives expected. As a matter of fact, well-organized communities had by-laws on the usage of lighting, community activities, new buildings, and even the use of smart lighting among the others practices, which made it easy for them to promote improvement of the health toughness of, as well as conflict-free environment in, the city (Taba, 2008). </p>
        <h2>Strategies for Reducing Light Pollution: Community Awareness and Technological Solutions</h2>
        <p>Shocking as it is however, areas that did not make effort to involve the communities or curved that effort shows nothing in the progress made on countering light pollution. It is because fundamentally there still is a gap in the approach in addressing this phenomenon.
        </p>
        <p>The findings of the research address unrevealed sides of light pollution including health and environmental problems that it causes. Over the years, the development of townships has been synonymous with increase in light pollution. Every new unit adds to the pool of artificial light contrasted by natural darkness begging for the need to do away with it.
        </p>
        <p>On the other hand, the effects of saturation of light levels have their toll especially on the nocturnal fauna due to their need of navigation, breeding and foraging. Consider the sea turtle, which makes use of the moon’s light, post hatching, to reach the ocean safely and end up getting disoriented by light from powered sources so as to have its numbers reduced (Witherington & Bjorndal, 1991). Moreover, the disturbance of these hunting behaviors has resulted in a decrease in the numbers of common food insects which a lot of bird species that exists in those environments eat, hence an effect on the wider community.
        </p>
        <p>And with the issue of light pollution, human health risks are an increasing concern. Even scientific evidence can testify that the exposure of the humankind to artificial lighting during the nighttime hours may cause disruptions in the normal sleep and wake cycle that may lead to growth of sleeping disorders and development of such chronic illnesses as obesity, stress, depression and anxiety (Haim & Zubeldat, 2015). The World Health Organization has acknowledged light pollution as a potential health hazard, especially tide over those who regularly work night shifts as well as people who live in boisterously illuminated cities (WHO, 2019).</p>
        <p>The arguments for this study clearly articulate measures that should be taken to curb light pollution. It is possible to effect such measures by the integration of smart lighting technologies to general infrastructure such that light is automatically dimmed based on different situations (Bright Outlook for Light at Night). In addition to this, the other aspect involves grassroots activities targeting the audiences and informing them it is possible to live in a world protected by dark sky. This kind of approaches are useful for effecting a change in residents’ attitudes making them become active proponents of appropriate light regimes in specific quarters.
        </p>
        <p>Proper enforcement of light Cal details under municipal policy as done by local administrators is important. Such rules can be said to be the pillars of sustainable development which promote zero light pollution and zero health and ecological risks to the inhabitants. Stakeholders especially urban city planners, residents, and conservation groups should form coalitions and promote all necessary laws addressing the challenge of light pollution.
        </p>
        <p>Reducing light pollution involves a combination of community awareness and technological advancements. Here are some effective strategies:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Install shielded outdoor lighting fixtures to direct light downward.</li>
            <li>Use energy-efficient bulbs that emit less blue light.</li>
            <li>Encourage local governments to implement "dark sky" policies that limit excessive lighting.</li>
            <li>Engage the community in awareness campaigns about the impacts of light pollution.</li>
        </ul>
